Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A tissue anchor system comprising: a support material; a suture engaged with the support material; an anchor comprising a body, a fin extending from the body in a first direction with an eyelet formed in the fin, a pair of radial barrels extending from the body in a radial direction perpendicular to the first direction, and a gripping tab removably attached to the fin, with the suture engaged with the eyelet of the fin; and an introducer having a cannula defining a bore sized to receive the body of the anchor and a slot formed in a wall of the cannula, with the slot sized to receive the fin of the anchor, and an ejection mechanism provided to eject the anchor out of the cannula. 2. The tissue anchor system of claim 1 , wherein the support material is porous and the suture is engaged with a pore of the support material. 3. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, wherein the suture is looped through the support material and the eyelet, with two ends of the suture sealed together to form a break pad. 4. The tissue anchor system of claim 1 , wherein the suture has two ends that are sealed together to form a break pad, and the break pad is thermally formed to be more brittle than a remaining portion of the suture. 5. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, wherein the suture has ends that are bonded together to form a continuous loop, with the suture looped through the support material and through the eyelet of the fin. 6. The tissue anchor system of claim 1 , wherein the cannula terminates in a bent end that is bent inward toward the bore to form a ramp. 7. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, wherein the cannula terminates in a pointed bent end that is located on a side of the cannula opposite from the slot. 8. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, wherein the fin and the radial barrels combine to provide the anchor with an asymmetric mass distribution and an asymmetric geometry with more mass located on a leading end portion of the anchor than on a trailing end portion. 9. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, wherein the fin extends from a first side of the body and the radial barrels are located on a second side of the body, and the fin provides the anchor with an asymmetric geometry with more geometric area located on the first side of the body than on the second side of the body. 10. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, further comprising: a crush rib formed between the pair of radial barrels on a side of the anchor opposite from the fin. 11. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, further comprising: a plication mechanism engaged with the support material, the plication mechanism provided as a single strand of suture that is looped three times into a three-circle configuration. 12. The tissue anchor system of claim 1, wherein the support material includes a base, a first arm extending away from the base, and a second arm extending away from the base and separated from the first arm, with the tissue anchor system comprising: a first suture looped through a first lateral side of the base and a first eyelet of a first anchor, a second suture looped through a second lateral side of the base and a second eyelet of a second anchor, 

 a third suture looped through the first arm of the support material and a third eyelet of a third anchor, and a fourth suture looped through the second arm of the support material and a fourth eyelet of a fourth anchor. 13. The tissue anchor system of claim 12, wherein each of the first suture, second suture, third suture, and the fourth suture is a closed loop having ends of each suture welded together into a pad. 14. The tissue anchor system of claim 12, wherein the ends of each suture is thermally welded together such that the pad is more brittle than a remaining portion of the closed loop. 15. A tissue anchor system comprising: a support having a base extending between a first lateral edge and an opposite second lateral edge of the support, a first pre-pubic arm extending contiguously along the first lateral edge of the support, a second pre-pubic arm extending contiguously along the second lateral edge of the support; a first suture having opposed ends that are bonded together to form a continuous loop, the first suture looped about the first lateral edge of the base and through a first eyelet of a first anchor; a second suture having opposed ends that are bonded together to form a continuous loop, the second suture looped about the second lateral edge of the base and through a second eyelet of a second anchor; a third suture having opposed ends that are bonded together to form a continuous loop, the third suture looped through the first pre-pubic arm of the support and through a third eyelet of a third anchor; a fourth suture having opposed ends that are bonded together to form a continuous loop, the fourth suture looped through the second pre-pubic arm of the support and through a fourth eyelet of a fourth anchor; 

 wherein each of the anchors has a body, a fin extending from the body in a first direction, a pair of rounded barrels extending from the body in a radial direction perpendicular to the first direction, and a gripping tab removably attached to the fin; and a cannula defining a bore sized to receive the body of each of the anchors and a slot formed in a wall of the cannula, with the slot sized to receive the fin of each of the anchors. 16. The tissue anchor system of claim 15, wherein the base has a base width extending between the first lateral edge and the opposite second lateral edge of the support, with the support formed in a shape of a V with a lateral distance between the first pre -pubic arm and the second pre-pubic arm measured at a location opposite of the base being larger than the base width and with a gap centrally formed between the first pre-pubic arm and the second pre-pubic arm. 17. The tissue anchor system of claim 15, further comprising: a plication mechanism engaged with the support between the base and the first and second pre-pubic arms. 18. The tissue anchor system of claim 17, wherein the plication mechanism is a single strand of suture that is looped three times into a three-circle configuration. 19. The tissue anchor system of claim 15, wherein the cannula terminates in a bent end that is bent inward toward the bore to form a ramp.
